OUT! CLEANED UP! Anrich Nortje with the double whammy! He is on a hat-trick now! David Warner came out to face just one ball here and his innings end on 200. Anrich Nortje goes for the yorker, but bowls a low full toss, on leg, David Warner looks to dig it out, but plays down the wrong line and the ball deflects off his pads to shatter the stumps again. David Warner make the walk back to a standing ovation. Australia five down now!
Commentary.Howout: b Anrich Nortje

Commentary.Commentary: David Warner walks out to bat now.

OUT! TIMBER! Anrich Nortje strikes in his second over! Travis Head goes back to the hut just after his half-century. Anrich Nortje bowls this on a good length and around leg, Travis Head looks to flick it away, but the ball skids through the surface and brushes off the pads to rattle the stumps. South Africa get the much-needed breakthrough.
Commentary.Howout: b Anrich Nortje

Commentary.Commentary: FIFTY FOR HEAD! He is having a great time out there and has continued his good form.This is short and on middle, Travis Head pulls it towards deep square leg for a brace.
This is on a good length and on leg, Travis Head looks to work it away but gets a leading edge down the pitch.
Another dot as this full delivery is knocked towards covers.
On a length and on off, Alex Carey defends it towards mid off.
Fuller one and on off, Alex Carey pushes it towards covers.
FOUR! Nice timing! Kagiso Rabada bowls this back of a length and on off, Alex Carey stays there and punches it wide of deep point for a boundary.
Full again and on off, Alex Carey drives it towards covers.
Kagiso Rabada begins with a full delivery as well and around off, angling away, Alex Carey looks to drive it but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Kagiso Rabada to bowl from the other end.
Length again and on leg, Alex Carey nudges it towards fine leg for one.
Back of a length and around off, Travis Head cuts it towards deep point for a run.
On a length and on off, Travis Head blocks it in front of short covers.
Goes fuller and on middle, Travis Head knocks it towards mid-wicket.
Sharp bouncer! Anrich Nortje bangs this short and on middle, Travis Head gets hurried but does well to duck under it.
Anrich Nortje start with a full delivery on leg, Alex Carey flicks it through square leg for a single.

We are all set for Day 3! The two umpires make their way out to the middle. The South African players can be seen in a huddle and now they are taking their respective field positions. Alex Carey and Travis Head walks out as they will look to extend the lead for Australia. Anrich Nortje to start proceedings with the ball. Let' play...
Update - 5 am IST (11.30 pm GMT, previous day) - There was some rain around in Melbourne so we will have a delayed start. Day 3 will begin at 5.15 am IST (11.45 pm GMT, previous day).

David Warner stole the show on Day 2 with his brilliant double hundred and put the Aussies in a solid position. Steven Smith also supported him well but just missed out on his hundred. However, their major concerns will be Cameron Green and Mitchell Starc, as both of them injured their fingers and are not sure if they can bowl or not. Warner also had to retire hurt, and it will be interesting to see if and when he comes out to bat again. South Africa, on the other hand, needs to make early inroads and try to get through the Australian innings quickly. Their best bets will be Anrich Nortje and Marco Jansen, who looked the most threatening. Day 3 is often called the Moving Day and this will paint us a better picture of things. Will the Aussies make their stronghold even more stronger? Or will the Proteas make a comeback? We will find out soon.

Hello and welcome to our coverage of Day 3 of the second Test between Australia and South Africa. The hosts are very much ahead in the game with a lead of 197 runs and seven wickets in hand, and they will look to take the game further away from the Proteas and stamp their authority.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, that is all from Day 2 and Australia lead by 197 runs. They are in a vey good position to extend their lead more as they have a lot of wickets in hand as well. South Africa, on the other hand will need to come up with better execution on Day 3 to get back in this game. The action on Day 3 begins at 5 am IST (11.30 pm GMT, previous day) on 28th December, Wednesday, but as you all know you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

South Africa will be disappointed with how things went on Day 2. At the start of the Day they were gifted a wicket but they just did not have any answers to the stand between David Warner and Steven Smith. There were a couple of half-chances here and there but they couldn't take it. However, in the third session a lot of things happened. Warner and Cameron Green retired hurt and the Proteas bowlers had a chance to get the breakthrough with the new ball, but is was not meant to be. Marco Jansen and Anrich Nortje looked the most threatening out of the lot and their aim will be to make early inroads on Day 3 to get back in this game.

Australia dominated all the sessions. David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne came out to bat with good intent but the latter sacrificed his wicket in the form of a run-out. Then came in Steven Smith and took control of the game along with Warner. Both of them added 239 runs for the third wicket. However, the headlines will be all about Warner as he scored a double century on his 100th Test and became the first Australian to do so and the second player after Joe Root to achieve this feat.. Although Smith missed out on his hundred, Warner stayed around untill his double ton and then had to retire hurt because of cramps due to the very hot conditions. After that it was Travis Head who continued his good form and scored runs briskly but the Aussies suffered another blow when Cameron Green also had to retire hurt after getting hit on his fingers while facing a delivery from Anrich Nortje. Head and Alex Carey finished things strongly for them.

Take a bow, David Warner! He absolutely smashed the Proteas attack all around the park and answered his critics in style. A day that well and truly belonged to the batters and especially Warner comes to an end. A total of 341 runs were scored and only two wickets fell. The conditions were very tough and credit goes to both set of players for giving their all to help their respective sides. At the end of Day 2, Australia are very much ahead in the game.
FOUR! Easy pickings! It is a length ball, down leg. Head stays back and glances it around the corner. It races away to the fine leg fence. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2.
On a length, on middle and leg, this one stays low. Head tucks it to mid-wicket.
On the pads, Carey stays back and clips it to deep square leg. They cross for one.
On off, pushed into covers.
Full and on the stumps. Carey drives it down the ground. Kagiso Rabada makes a solid stop with his feet.
FOUR! Find the gap really well. It is overpitched, outside off. Carey shuffles and carves it through the gap at covers for four runs. This is a good-looking shot.
FOUR! Nicely played! It is full, and down leg. Head gets low and sweeps it behind square on the leg side for a boundary. He moves to 44 now.
Fuller, wide of off. Head knocks it to long off.
Short, on fourth stump. Head pushes it out.
Head presses forward and blocks this full delivery back to the bowler.
Tossed up, on off, defended on the front foot.
Lungi Ngidi is suffering from cramps now. He is going off the field as well. Keshav Maharaj to complete this over.
Length, angled across the left-hander. Carey taps it through covers for a single.
A short ball, on middle. This one gets bigger on the batsman. Head hops inside the crease with his blade near his face. It pops up but lands safely on the leg side.
A length ball, around off. Carey looks to punch it away. It goes to the leg side off the inside edge. They take a quick single.
Much fuller, on off stump. Carey pushes it towards mid off with full face of the blade.
Alex Carey steps across to this length ball and blocks it out watchfully.
A length ball, on middle. Carey tucks it to the leg side.
A length ball, outside off. Head reaches out and hammers it through the gap at covers. Dean Elgar gives it a chase and keeps it down to three runs.
Kagiso Rabada comes back into the attack.
Bangs it in short, wide outside off. Carey lets it be.
It is a short ball, outside off. a bit close to the batter. Carey looks to go for the cut shot but misses it completely.
This is outside off, left alone by Carey.
Back of a length, wide of off. Head latches onto it and cuts it through covers. They take a single.
A short ball, in the channel of uncertainty. Head leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full and on off, blocked back to the bowler.
Anrich Nortje dishes a short ball, on top of off. Carey stays back and fends it out.
Good length, around off. Carey defends it into covers.
Anrich Nortje cuts the batter in half now. It is quite short, on middle. Carey hops inside the crease and tries to flick it away but gets beaten on the inside edge.
This is full, on middle and leg. Carey clips it to the leg side.
Length and on off, blocked out,
A short ball, on leg. Head stays back and tries to flick it away. The ball goes to square leg off his thigh pads. They cross for a leg bye.
Much fuller, outside off, shaping in a touch. Carey pushes it to the man at mid off. Just a single off the over then.
Fraction short, on off. Carey taps it to point.
This is full and outside off. Carey leans in and drives it into covers.
On  a length, on top of off. Head opens the face and dabs it down past backward point for a single.
A short ball, on off. Head hops and blocks it to the off side.
Jansen starts with a full one, sliding down leg. Head misses his flick.
It is a short ball, angled down leg. Carey looks to heave it across the line but it lobs off the top-edge and lands in front of him.
It is a half-volley, around off. Carey drives it down the ground. The batters take two runs before the fielder cuts it out.

Halt! Cameron Green has been hit on his fingers on the previous delivery and there is some blood. The physio is in to check on him. He is going off the field now as he will not be able to continue. Alex Carey comes out to the middle now.
Ouch! Cameron Green is looking in some discomfort and is unable to continue. A blow to the batting team as Cameron Green is retired hurt.

A short ball, coming into the batter, from outside off. It gets big on the batter. Green hops inside his crease, closes the face and blocks it to the leg side, although off his gloves, as he gets hit hard on his right hand, on the top of the blade.
Green tucks this length ball, off his hips, towards the man at short leg.
Full, on the pads, Head flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
This is a good-length delivery, on top of off. Head stays back and deals with it.
FOUR! Wonderful shot! It is full, around off. Green steps forward and drives it down the ground for a boundary at long off.
A length ball, wide of off. Green looks to play at it but misses.
Back of a length, angled across, outside off. Green taps it into covers.
Fraction short, in the channel, swinging in a touch late. Green shoulders his arms at it.
Length ball, angling away. Green lets it be.
A length ball, angled down leg. Head stays back and clips it to square leg for a single.

Drinks! The second time a drinks break has been taken in this session and righly so because of the hot conditions out there. Travis Head looks in good touch and Cameron Green just need to calm. South Africa will want to take a few wickets with the new ball taken.
Green is finally off the mark now! It is full, on middle and leg. Green stays back and flicks it to deep mid-wicket. They take two as there is protection in the deep.
On off, defended out. Green is yet to get off the mark here.
A well-directed short ball, on the bodyline. It climb onto the batter. Green lobs it behind short leg, who is unable to get to the ball in time. It lands safely as it lobs of his blade.
Anrich Nortje fires in a yorker, in the blockhole, at around 144 km/h. Green stays back and digs it out right in time.
Overpitched, outside off. Green steps across and strokes it into covers.
This one shapes in from outside off, on a good length. Green offers full face of the blade.
FOUR! Travis Head is on a roll here. It is full and on middle. Head flicks it aerially towards the cow corner. It goes for four runs.
Full and on off. Head blocks it out solidly.
This is a length ball, outside off. Head leaves it alone for the keeper.
A length ball, wide outside off, shaping away a touch. Head looks to block it away but gets beaten on the outside edge.
SIX! All the way! It is too full and straight attacking the pads. Travis Head stays back and powers it over the square leg fence for a biggie. Wonderful use of the wrists this time.
Jansen dishes a length ball, outside off. Head lets it be.
Marco Jansen replaces Keshav Maharaj.
Green serves it on a length, wide of off. Green has no shot to offer.
This is outside off, left alone.
BEATEN! A length ball, in the channel. Green hangs his blade away from the body to get beaten on the outside edge.
A length ball, wide of off. Head dabs it down to third man for one.
A length ball, around off. Head hangs back and defends it out.
Anrich Nortje starts with a sharp bouncer on middle. Head ducks under it.
The new ball is available now and Dean Elgar wastes no time on opting for the same. Will the second new ball bring any change in fortunes for South Africa?
Short and on middle, Cameron Green blocks it out.
Flatter, full and on middle, Travis Head eases it towards long on for a run.

FOUR! Another boudnary for Head! This is short again and outside off, Travis Head moves back and slaps it towards the deep point fence where Anrich Nortje tries his best running from his left, but fails to stop the boundary.
Shortish and on middle, Travis Head tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Floated, full and on off, Travis Head uses his feet and strokes it towards mid off.
Angles this into the batter, short and on leg, Travis Head works it towards square leg.
Length again and on off, angling in, Cameron Green blocks it out.
On a length and around leg, Travis Head helps it towards fine leg for a single.
Full again and on off, Travis Head mistimes his drive towards the bowler.

Full and on middle, Travis Head drives it back to the bowler where Lungi Ngidi picks it up and throws at the batter's end where the ball hits the bat of Head as he tries to get away from the line of the ball.
FOUR! Two in a row! This is back of a length and outside off, Travis Head punches it in front of square on the off side for a boundary.
FOUR! A poor delivery and rightly punished! This is short and outside off, Travis Head slices it over point for a boundary.
Another dot as this full delivery is driven back to the bowler.
Quicker, full and on middle, Cameron Green knocks it back to the bowler.
Floated, full and on middle, Travis Head looks to drive it but gets an outside edge towards point for a single.
On middle, blocked out.
Short and on leg, Travis Head tucks it towards square leg.
Tossed up, full and on off, Travis Head drives it towards short covers.
Ouch! David Warner is down with cramps again and it does not look good this time as he will not be able to continue. Cameron Green walks out to bat now.

EDGE AND FOUR! DOUBLE HUNDRED FOR WARNER! Lungi Ngidi bowls this on a good length and on off, David Warner looks to push it away, but gets an outside edge past slip cordon for a boundary. He becomes the first Australian player to score a double-ton on their 100th Test match. He still has some energy left for his trademark celebratin and he soaks in all the applause. This has been a fine effort from him and he has written history here. A day to remember for Warner!
Full and on the pads, Travis Head tucks it towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Nicely played! This is back of a length and on off, Travis Head stays there and punches it from the middle of the bat towards the deep point fence for a boundary.
Short and way outside off, David Warner reaches for it and taps it through point for a run.
Fuller and on off, David Warner drives it straight to covers.
Back of a length and on off, David Warner blocks it out down the pitch.
Lungi Ngidi comes back into the attack.
A bit short and around leg, David Warner works it towards square leg for one.
Quicker, full and on middle, David Warner drills it back to the bowler.
Another short delivery, on middle, David Warner goes for the pull shot, but gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Short again and on leg, Travis Head flicks it through square leg for one.
Short and on middle, turning in, Travis Head moves back and pushes it back to the bowler.
Tossed up, full and on middle, David Warner reverse-sweeps it towards point for a single.
Anrich Nortje bangs in a sharp bouncer, on middle, Travis Head ducks under it.
Length again and on off, David Warner punches it towards covers where the fielder makes a half-stop. They cross.
Short of a length and on middle, angling in, David Warner knocks it towards mid on.
This is on a good length and on off, David Warner backs away and goes for the cut, but misses.
Back of a length and on leg, Travis Head nudges it towards fine leg for a single.
Travis Head comes out to the middle now.

OUT! TAKEN! Anrich Nortje strikes right after drinks! South Africa finally breaks this partnership and there is a sense of relief among their players. Anrich Nortje bowls this short of a length and on off, Steven Smith looks to upper cut it, but the ball keeps a bit low and takes the bottom edge to go straight into the Theunis de Bruyn at gully who makes no mistake. Steven Smith is really disappointed with himself as he departs on 85. Australia lose their third.
Commentary.Howout: c Theunis de Bruyn b Anrich Nortje

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks! Australia have dominated proccedings here and now both David Warner and Steven Smith are changing gears and scoring runs quickly. South Africa are in desperate need of wickets here. Also, David Warner is receiving further treatment. Anrich Nortje to bowl after the break.
Short again and outside off, David Warner punches it through covers for a couple of runs.
Slightly shorter and on off, David Warner carves it through covers for a brace. He moves into 190s now.
Flighted and on middle, Steven Smith uses his feet and forces it towards long on for a run.
Short and on middle, David Warner pulls it through mid-wicket for a single.
SIX! Up, up and away! This is floated, full and on off, David Warner launches it over the deep mid-wicket fence for a biggie.
FOUR! Powered away! This is tossed up, full and on off, David Warner thrashes it wide of mid off for a boundary.
Back of a length and on off, Steven Smith steers it towards gully.
Full and on off, Steven Smith blocks it out to the off side.
A slower one, on a length and on off, David Warner pushes it through cover-point for a single.
Short again and on middle, David Warner pulls it wide of deep square leg for a brace.

Short of a length and on middle, David Warner looks to pull it away, but misses as the ball brushes off the pads and goes through to the keeper. There is an appeal for caught behind but turned down. South Africa take the review but is wasted as replays confirms no bat involved.
This is on a hard length and on middle, angling in, David Warner misses and gets hit on his pads.
Shortish and on middle, Steven Smith nudges it towards mid-wicket.
Tossed up, full and on middle, Steven Smith leans on and defends.
Flatter, full and on leg, Steven Smith goes down and paddles it towards fine leg for a couple of runs.
Floated, full and on middle, Steven Smith lobs it in front of deep mid-wicket for a brace.
Short adn on middle, David Warner pulls it through square leg for a single.
SIX! BOOM! David Warner is in the mood here! This is tossed up, full and on middle, David Warner goes down and slog-sweeps it over the deep mid-wicket fence for a biggie.
Short and on middle, David Warner pulls it towards deep square leg for a single.
Full and on middle, David Warner chips it in the air, but it lands safely behind mid on as the batters complete two runs.
Back of a length and on off, David Warner dabs it towards point.
FOUR! Up and over! This is full and on middle, David Warner stays there and lofts it over mid off for a boundary.
Short of a length and on middle, David Warner looks to pull it away, but gets hurried as the ball hits him on the stomach area.
Full and on off, Steven Smith drives it through covers for a run.
On a length and on off, Steven Smith leaves it alone. It is called a no ball for overstepping.
This is almost on a yorker length and on middle, Steven Smith jams it out towards long on for a run. 200-run partnership comes up with that between these two batters.
Tossed up, full and on middle, Steven Smith knocks it back to the bowler.
A bit short and on middle, Steven Smith defends it off the back foot.
On middle, blocked out.
Floated, full and on middle, Steven Smith blocks it out.
Tossed up, on middle, David Warner comes down the track and drives it towards long on for a single.
Back of a length and on off, David Warner punches it though point for run.
Short again and on middle, Steven Smith pulls it wide of deep square leg for one.
FOUR! Steven Smith gets into the act now! This is short and on middle, Steven Smith picks up the length early and pulls it towards the deep square leg fence for a boundary.
This is on a good length and around off, Steven Smith lets it go to the keeper.
Back of a length and on off, David Warner cuts it towards sweeper cover for a single.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Kagiso Rabada bowls this short and outside off, David Warner frees his arms and punches it past covers for a boundary.
Fires this one full and on the pads, David Warner tucks it towards mid-wicket for one.

FOUR! Good shot! This is flighted, full and on middle, David Warner goes down and heaves it towards the deep mid-wicket fence where the fielder tries to keep it in but fails to do so. 150 up for David Warner!
Tossed up, full and on off, David Warner defends it back to the bowler.
Floated, full and on middle, David Warner blocks it out.
Short again and on middle, David Warner forces it towards wide of long on for a couple of runs.
Short and outside off, David Warner cuts it uppishly but wide of short cover for a brace.
Length again and on middle, Steven Smith blocks it to the leg side.
Back of a length and on middle, Steven Smith knocks it towards mid on.
FOUR! Great shot! Lungi Ngidi lands this short and on middle, Steven Smith stays there and pulls it towards the deep square leg fence for a boundary.
Full and on middle, David Warner tucks it towards deep square leg for a run.
A slower delievry again, on a length and on middle, angling in, David Warner gets cramped and keeps it out to the leg side.
FOUR! Deft touch! This is on a hard length and outside off, David Warner stays there and just guides it wide of third man for a boundary.
Darts this one full and on off, Steven Smith drives it towards short covers.
Shortish and on off, Steven Smith strides forward and pushes it towards covers.
On middle, blocked out.
Floated and around off, Steven Smith defends it to the off side.
Tossed up, full and on middle, Steven Smith blocks it out.
Short and on middle, David Warner flicks it off the back foot through square leg for a run.
Full and on off, Steven Smith drives it towards mid off.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Lungi Ngidi bowls this on a good length and outside off, Steven Smith waits for it and steers it past short third man for a boundary.
This is on a hard length and on middle, Steven Smith looks to play at it, but the extra bounce takes the ball past his bat and he gets hit on his thumb.
FOUR! In the gap! This is short and on middle, Steven Smith swivels and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boudnary.
Back of a length and on leg, David Warner helps it towards fine leg for a single.
A full toss, on off, David Warner drills it straigh to short covers.
Flatter, full and on off, Steven Smith drives it towards short covers.
Looped up, full and on off, David Warner guides it with the outer half through point for one.
Tossed up, full and on off, David Warner pushes it towards covers.
Short again and on off, David Warner punches it towards covers.
Short and outside off, Steven Smith cuts it towards point and sets off for the run. The fielder there hits the stumps a the batter's end but Warner is in.
Floated, short and on leg, David Warner flicks it towards square leg for a single.
We are ready for the final session! The players are making their way out in the middle now. David Warner and Steven Smith to continue for Australia. Keshav Maharaj to continue after the break.
... Day 2, Sesson 3 ...

A session that is truly dominated by Australia. They managed to score 95 runs in 27 over without losing any wicket. David Warner and Steven Smith came out on the crease and continued on their merry way. This is the first time ever they stitched a 150-run partnership in Test cricket. They head into the break with a lead of 42 runs. The conditions have been pretty tough in this hottest afternoon session. South African bowlers had to toil hard under the sun. Dean Elgar tried to various different combinations with the ball but none could find any success. It is pretty evident that the conditions are favourable for the batters at the moment. Also, there are more 17 overs to go before the new ball comes into equation. The South African bowlers have their task out and need something more than a miracle to get them back into this competition. Another enticing session of cricket coming your way. Do join us at 10 am IST (4.30 am GMT), to find out how things pan out.
A slower one now, full and on middle, Steven Smith works it with the inner half through square leg for a brace. That will be TEA ON DAY 2!
Length again and on off, Steven Smith pushes it towards covers.
Full but down the leg this time, Steven Smith leaves it alone.
A good bouncer now, on middle, Steven Smith ducks under it.
Back of a length and on off, Steven Smith blocks it to the off side.
Short of a length and on middle, David Warner swats it towards deep square leg for a single.
A bit short and on off, Steven Smith moves back and punches it towards point.
On off, kept out.
Short and on off, David Warner pushes it towards wide of covers for a run.
Flatter and around middle, David Warner uses his feet and works it towards mid-wicket.
Tossed up, full and on off, David Warner blocks it out.
Floated, full and on off, Steven Smith eases it towards long off for a single.
Short again and on middle, Steven Smith pulls it through square leg for one more.
Marco Jansen lands this short and on middle, David Warner pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for one. That brings up the 150-run partnership between these two batters.
Full again and on off, Steven Smith drills it towards covers where the fielder parries it to mid off. They cross.
Full and on middle, Steven Smith drives it straight to mid on.
This is on a good length and around off, Steven Smith lifts his bat up and lets it go to the keeper.
Back of a length and on off, Steven Smith punches it towards covers.
Shorter in length and on off, David Warner mistimes his cut back towards the bowler.
Looped up, full and on off, Steven Smith drives it towards long off for a run.
Tossed up, full and on off, Steven Smith leans on and blocks it out.
Fires in a yorker now, on middle, Steven Smith digs it back to the bowler.
Short and on middle, David Warner forces it through square leg for one.
Floated and around middle, David Warner uses his feet and blocks it down the pitch.
Short and on off this time, Steven Smith pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Fuller again and on off, Steven Smith defends it to the off side.
Fuller one and on middle, David Warner drives it towards mid off for a run. Oh..no! It is called a no ball for overstepping.
Marco Jansen bowls this on a hard length and on leg, angling in, David Warner misses his flick as the ball loops up off his pads into the hands of gully.
On a length and on middle, David Warner knocks it towards mid on.
Goes short and on middle, Steven Smith pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
This is on a good length and on off, Steven Smith pushes it towards covers.
Tossed up, full and on off, Steven Smith goes down and scoops it towards fine leg for a run.
Flighted delivery, full and on off, David Warner guides it towards point for a single.
A bit short and around off, David Warner stays back and keeps it away.
Quicker one, full and on middle, David Warner defends it on the front foot.
Floated, short and on middle, David Warner blocks it out.
FOUR! Fine shot! This is tossed up, full and on middle, David Warner goes down and slog-sweeps it towards the vacant deep mid-wicket fence for a boundary.
FOUR! Steven Smith brings up his half-century in fine fashion. It is a short ball, wide outside off. Steven Smith rides the bounce and cuts it along the ground through point for a boundary.
Length ball, outside off. Warner eases it to point for a quick single.
A short ball, sliding down leg. Warner drags his pull to short fine.
This one is angled into the pads. Smith tucks it behind square on the leg side for one.
Marco Jansen serves this one on a length, wide of off from 'round the wicket. Smith lets it be.
Jansen dishes it full, outside off. Smith drives it on the up but straight to the man at covers.
Marco Jansen is back on.
On middle and leg, flicked to square leg.
Flatter and on off. Warner pats it back to the bowler.
Halt! David Warner is struggling with some cramps here. The physio is in to check on him. He is ready to continue.
This is full and on leg. Warner sweeps it towards square leg. Lungi Ngidi dives to his right and stop the ball with one hand. It looks like Warner might've hurt himself by getting back up here.
David Warner comes down the track and defends this full delivery to short mid on.
On off, blocked out watchfully.
It is short, turning into the batter. David Warner stays back and pulls it to deep mid-wicket. They take a couple.
David Warner flicks this good-length delivery off his hips to square leg for one.
A length ball, right in the channel. Warner gets behind and defends it away.
Length, on off, defended out.

OH NO! Kyle Verreynne has his hands on his head as he remains on the floor. It is a length ball, sliding down leg. Warner looks to flick it away but misses. It goes off his thigh pads to the right of the keeper. Kyle Verreynne dives to that side but it comes off his gloves. The ball is about to hit the helmet placed behind him but a fielder comes in quickly and collects it. Although, the replays later confirm that there is no bat on it. Kyle Verreynne shouldn't be gutted anymore.
A low full toss, angled across the left-hander, outside off. Warner works it to the man at point.
Full length, on fourth stump. Warner opens the face and pushes it to cover.
Pushed through quicker and fuller, on off. Smith blocks into covers on his front foot.
On middle and leg, Smith defends it into the deck.
Warner flicks it to square leg off his hips for a single.
Touch short, on off. Warner flicks it to mid-wicket.
This one turns in from outside off to hit Warner high on his pads as he comes down the track to block it away.
Slower through the air, full and on off. Smith knocks it down to long on for one.
LEG BYE! Very full, shaping down leg. Smith misses his flick. It brushes his pads and rolls down to fine leg. They cross for a leg bye.
This is on a length, outside off, nips in off the deck. Steven Smith defends it out.
David Warner cuts this short ball towards deep point. They take a single.
Good length, outside off. Warner shuffles and defends it out watchfully.
Full length, wide of off. Warner drives it to covers but not in the gap.
A length ball, shaping down leg. Warner does not bother.
Lungi Ngidi comes back into the attack now.
This is straying on the pads. Warner goes back and clips it to the leg side for a single now.
Attacking the stumps with a length ball, Warner hangs back and blocks it away.
On off, defended out.
A single now as this is eased down to long off.

Lands short! It is looped up, full and on off. It grips and turns away a touch. Smith dances down the track and looks to flick it across the line. The ball takes the outside edge but lands short of the man at gully.
Tosses it up and full. David Warner flicks it down to long on from outside off, He crosses for one.

Drinks! Australia have taken the lead now thanks to David Warner and Steven Smith for their brilliant partnership. They are well set and will not give their wicket easily. South African bowlers need to produce something special to break this partnership and get back in the game or else this could go out of their hands pretty quickly.
Kagiso Rabada bangs in a bouncer, on off, Steven Smith sways away from it.
Another short delivery, on off, David Warner pulls it through mid-wicket for one. Australia lead by 5 runs now.
Short and on middle, Steven Smith pulls it towards deep square leg for a run.
Goes fuller this time, on off, slower too, David Warner drives it through covers for a single.
This is on a good length and on middle, David Warner knocks it back to the bowler.
Full and on off. Smith drives it straight down the ground for three runs.

NO BALL! The South African celebrations have been cut short here as Kagiso Rabada oversteps. Although, it could've been ruled out soon after if it was not for the no ball, as Steven Smith was sure that he got pinged on his arms rather than gloving it. Coming to the delivery. It is a short ball, on middle and leg. Smith goes for the pull but is a touch early into his shot. The ball lobs off his back hand and Kyle Verreynne gathers it safely. Kagiso Rabada appeals and the umpire his finger after giving it some thought. Steven Smith signals for a review straightaway but it is not required as the umpire signals a no ball for overstepping.
Loops it up, full and on off. Warner blocks it on his front foot.
Flatter and on off. David Warner defends it out watchfully.
Around off, blocked back to the bowler.
Much fuller and on leg. Steven Smith flicks it aerially over mid-wicket. Anrich Nortje gives it a long chase and keeps it down to three runs.
Tosses it up, around off. Steven Smith gets forward and blocks it out.
Keshav Maharaj drags his length back, on leg. David Warner flicks it through square leg and crosses.
Warner punches this length ball to point. There is a misfield which allows the batter to take a single.
Touch fuller, shaping into the batter, on leg. Smith shuffles a bit and flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Length, on top of off. Smith keeps his eyes on the ball and defends it with a straight bat.
On a good length, outside off. It climbs on the batter. Steven Smith tries to punch it through the line but it dies in front of him off the inside edge.
This is sliding down leg, Smith lets it be.
Back of a length, outside off. David Warner swivels and pulls it along the ground to deep square leg for a single.
Flatter one, on leg. David Warner stays back and flicks it in front of square on the leg side for a single.
This is down leg. Warner sweeps it to short fine.
It is full and on off. Warner presses forward and pushes it back to the bowler.
On off, blocked out.
David Warner gets down on one knee for this full delivery and reverse sweeps it to past point for a couple.
Loops it full and on off. Smith strokes it down to long off for an easy single.
A length ball, angled in from outside off. David Warner blocks it off his back foot.
Full and on off, defended out.
A length ball, sliding down leg. Warner tries to pull it away but drags it to the right of the keeper. Kyle Verreynne is quick to slide to his right and make a sharp stop.
A length ball, on fourth stump. Warner blocks it out solidly.
Steven Smith flicks it off his hips to mid-wicket for a single.
It is on a fuller length, on middle and leg. Warner goes back and flicks it through mid-wicket for three runs. The stand moves to 100 runs.
Flatter, on middle, Steven Smith stays back and defends it again.
Slower through the air, on off, Steven Smith opens the face of his bat and guides it towards point.
Tossed up, full and on off, Steven Smith blocks it out.
Steven Smith uses his feet and turns this short delivery towards mid-wicket for no run.
Short and on middle, David Warner tucks it towards square leg for a single.
FOUR! Nice shot! This is floated, full and on middle, David Warner goes down and whips it away towards the deep mid-wicket fence for a boundary.
Length again and on middle, Steven Smith defends it to the leg side.
On a length and on middle, Steven Smith tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Goes fuller and on middle, Steven Smith blocks it out.
This is on a good length and outside off, Steven Smith lets it go to the keeper.
Full and on leg, David Warner flicks it through square leg for a single.

FOUR! HUNDRED FOR WARNER! He marks his 100th Test with a ton. He certainly needed this knock to boost his confidence after a lean patch in the recent years. Kagiso Rabada lands this short and down the leg, David Warner pulls it towards the fine leg fence for a boundary. He celebrates the moment by taking off his helmet and acknowledges the crowd.
A bit short and on off, Steven Smith moves back and pushes it towards covers.
Looped up, on leg, David Warner comes down the track and drills it towards long on for a run.
Flatter, full and on middle, David Warner knocks back to the bowler.
Floated, short and on off, David Warner blocks it out.
Short and on middle, David Warner defends it on the back foot.
Tossed up, full and on middle, David Warner goes down and sweeps it wide of deep square leg for a brace. He moves to 95!
Another good bouncer, on middle and leg, Steven Smith ducks underneath it.
Short of a length and on leg, David Warner turns it towards square leg for a single.
Quickest delivery of the match so far! This is full and on middle at 155 clicks, David Warner knocks it with the inner half towards mid on.

FOUR BYES! Anrich Nortje bangs in bouncer on middle, takes off from the surface, David Warner ducks under it and Kyle Verreynne behind the stumps fails to reach it with his leap as the ball races towards the fence for a boundary.
Goes fuller this time and outside off, David Warner mistimes his drive towards mid off.
On a length and on off, David Warner cuts it towards point.
Flighted delivery, full and on middle, Steven Smith is solid in his defense again.
Gives this one some air, on off, Steven Smith leans on and defends it to the off side.
Quicker one, full and on middle, Steven Smith blocks it down the pitch.
A bit short and on off, Steven Smith pushes it off the back foot towards covers.
Tossed up, full and on off, turning away, Steven Smith leaves it alone.
Floated, full and on off, David Warner uses his feet and drives it towards mid off for a single.
Back of a length and on middle, David Warner works it through square leg for one.
Anrich Nortje nails the yorker this time, on off, angling in, David Warner does really well to get his bat down in time and keeps it out.
Short of a length and on leg, Steven Smith gets cramped a bit and helps it towards short fine leg for a run.
Full but down the leg side, Steven Smith lets it go to the keeper.
Back of a length and outside off, David Warner slaps it towards deep point for a single. He moves into the 90s now.
This is on a good length and on middle, angling in, David Warner looks to block it but gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Shortish and on middle, Steven Smith keeps it out.
Tossed up, full and on off, Steven Smith defends it on the front foot.
Keshav Maharaj continues with his shorter length, outside off this time, Steven Smith cuts it but finds covers.
Slightly shorter and on leg, David Warner nudges it towards short fine leg for a single.
Short again and around off, David Warner defends it down the pitch.
Short and on middle, turning in, David Warner blocks it towards short leg.
Full and on off, Steven Smith defends it towards the short cover region.
Short and outside off, David Warner steers it towards deep point for a single.
Back of a length and on middle, David Warner hops up a bit and blocks it to the off side.
Anrich Nortje bangs in a fiery bouncer now, on middle, David Warner goes for the pull shot but fails to connect.
This is on a hard length and on off, angling in again, David Warner bunts it onto the ground as the ball goes nowehere.
Anrich Nortje bowls this on a good length at 152 clicks, on off, angling in, David Warner looks to cut it from close to his body but misses.
Another dot as this short delievery is blocks it towards silly point.
Shortish and on off, Steven Smith punches it towards covers.
Floated, short and off, Steven Smith uses his feet and knocks it past silly point.
On middle, blocked out.
A bit short and on off, Steven Smith defends it on the back foot.
SIX! BANG! Steven Smith goes big now! This is tossed up and around middle, Steven Smith dances down the track and smokes it over the wide long on fence for a biggie.
Keshav Maharaj to bowl from the other end.
Back of a length and on off, Steven Smith taps it in front of covers for a quick single.

FOUR! Just over! Anrich Nortje bowls a good short delivery, on middle at 151 clicks, Steven Smith goes for the pull shot but gets hurried as the ball takes the top edge and flies just over the keeper for a boudnary.
Length again and on off, Steven Smith pushes it towards covers.
This is on a good length and outside off, Steven Smith leaves it alone.
Back of a length and around leg, David Warner pulls it towards deep square leg for a single.
Short of a length and on off, David Warner stays there and blocks it out towards the bowler.

We are back for the second session! The South African players are in a huddle near the ropes and are making their way out in the middle now. David Warner and Steven Smith walks out to continue the batting for Australia. Anrich Nortje to bowl.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

South Africa, on the other hand were gifted a wicket early in the session, but failed to build on that and let Australia take control of the game. Although, Marco Jansen and Lungi Ngidi troubled the batters, they did not manage to get the breakthrough. Their aim will be to break this partnership as quickly as possible after Lunch and get into the middle order of the Aussies. Will they be able to do it? Or will the Aussies continue to rack up the runs? We will find out in a bit. Do join us at 7.40 am IST (2.10 am GMT) for the post-Lunch session.

Lunch Break! Australia are trailing by 53 runs now with eight wickets in hand and are in a strong position at the moment. David Warner looks like a man on a mission and is well set to get a hundred on his 100th Test match while Steven Smith has provided him the required support. They did lose Marnus Labuschagne to a mix-up as he ran himself out, but after that it has been a good session for them. Now, this pair will look to come out for the post-Lunch session and go past the total to give Aussies the lead.
Loops it up, full and on off. Smith defends it out solidly. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 2.
Full and on off, driven to long off for a signle.
On off, blocked out.
Flatter and on off, defended back to the bowler.
On off, defended back to the bowler once again.
It is full and on off. Warner dances down the track and works it back to the bowler.
Back of a length and outside off, Steven Smith shoulders arms to it.
Nice delivery! This is on a good length and around off, Steven Smith looks to block it out, but the ball just goes past the outside edge towards the keeper.
Full and on off, Steven Smith blocks it out.

Is it toe first? Dean Elgar seems to be interested and takes a review for lbw. It is a full delivery, angled in on off. Smith tries to dig it out but it gets pinged on his pads first. Later it goes through the off side off his bat and they run two. The review is taken and the Ball Tracking confirms that the impact is outside the line. South Africa lose a review here.
Steven Smith leaves it alone as this is served outside off.
WIDE! Very full. wide outside off. The umpire signals a wide straightaway.
Jansen comes from 'round the wicket and angles it in on a length, around off. It shapes away a touch off the deck. Smith trie to chase it but gets beaten.
Quicker and full, outside off. Warner blocks it back to the bowler on the front foot.
Touch short, Warner goes back and defends it out.
Loops it up, full and on off. Warner presses forward and pushes it to cover.
Flatter one, on the pads. Warner tucks it to the leg side.
This is pushed through full and on off. Smith pushes it to mid off and crosses.
It is full and outside off. Warner flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Short of a length and on off, Steven Smith offers no shot at it.
FOUR! Easy pickings for Smith! This is short and outside off, Steven Smith slices it over point for a boundary.
A sharp bouncer, on middle, Steven Smith ducks under it.
FOUR! This has been put away! Marco Jansen lands this short and on middle, Steven Smith stands tall and pulls it towards the deep square leg fence for a boundary.
BEATEN! Marco Jansen serves this full and on off, Steven Smith goes for the driver but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Back of a length and outside off, Steven Smith leaves it alone.
On middle and leg, tucked to the leg side.
On off, defended out.
Pushed through quicker and on off. Smith nudges it to the leg side.
On off, defended out.
Fuller, wide of off. Warner leans in and drives it through covers for three runs.

FOUR RUNS! David Warner becomes only the eighth batsman for Australia to score 8000 runs in this format. He gets soaked with applauds. It is tossed up, full and outside off. David Warner carves it through covers. The fielder makes a solid stop in the deep but the batters run four anyways.
Keshav Maharaj comes into the attack now.
A single now as this is clipped to the leg side.
It is full and on off. Warner pushes it down the ground. Steven Smith tries to get out of the way but gets it to stop instead.
A length ball, outside off. Warner defends it out watchfully.

FOUR! Nothing is going South African's way here. It is a length balll, on off. David Warner gets a thick inside edge as he tries to push it through covers. The ball scoots past the stump and races down to the fine leg fence.
This is on a good length, with some extra bounce, outside off. Warner leaves it alone.
On a length, wide outside off. Warner has no shot to offer.
Good length, on fifth stump. Smith shuffles and blocks it away.
Touch short, outside off. Smith leaves it alone.
On off, defended out.

DROPPED! Kyle Verreynne is unable to gather the ball safely and Steven Smith gets another chance at the crease. It is a short ball, angling down leg. Smith goes for the pull but only manages to glove it to the left of the keeper. Kyle Verreynne dives to that side but it spills out of his gloves.
Good running! David Warner gets into the 70s. It is very full, on middle and leg. David Warner drives it down the ground towards long on. They take three.
Quite full, wide of off. Smith tries to drive it through the off side but gets it to square leg off the inside edge. They take one.
A length ball, around off. Warner gets it to the man at gully off the outer half.
Full, on fifth stump, left alone.
A length ball, outside off. Smith steps across and punches it to the left of mid off. They take a quick single before the fielder cuts it out.
David Warner drives this full delivery to sweeper cover from outside off. The batters cross for a single.
Much fuller, on off. Warner blocks it with full face.
A length ball, angled in from 'round the wicket, on top of off. Warner opens the face and guides it to the off side.
This is outside off and Smith leaves it alone for the keeper.
An in-tucker this time, on a fuller length. Smith shuffles and nudges it to the leg side.
Very full, wide of off, swinging in a bit. Smith looks to go for the drive but gets it to the leg side off the inner half.
Jansen bends his back hard and serves a hard length ball, in the channel. Steven Smith lets it be.
A sharp bouncer, wide of off. Smith tries to chase it but misses. This one is just whiskers away from the outside edge.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Smith clips it to square leg.
LEG BYE! Good length, shaping down leg. Smith misses his flick. It brushes the pads and goes down to fine leg. They cross for a leg bye.
Lungi Ngidi serves it full, swinging into the pads. Smith flicks it towards mid on.
Outside off, left alone.
Fraction short, on top of off. David Warner hops inside the crease and defends it to point for a single.
Back of a length, on fifth stump. This one holds its line. David Warner watches it sail past him.
Good lenght, angled into the pads. Warner nudges it to the leg side.
Good movement! It is full and wide outside off. The ball swings in a long way off the deck. Steven Smith is not bothered by the movement here and makes a sharp leave.
Much fuller, outside off. Smith across and defends it to cover-point.
Jansen comes 'round the wicket. The seamer angles in a length ball. Smith lets it be.
Some width on offer as Jansen serves it on a length, wide of off. Warner cuts it towards point and crosses.
A length ball, shaping away from the left-hander. David Warner blocks it out.
Quite full, on fifth stump, it nips away off the deck. David Warner makes a good leave.
Steven Smith blocks this length ball safely. 5 runs off the over. The bowlers are finding it really hard to cause any trouble here.
A good-length ball, outside off, shapes in a bit later. Steven Smith makes a good leave.
Back of a length, wide of off. Warner plays it late and dabs it to deep point for a single. 100 is up for Australia.
FOUR! Perfectly placed. It is very full, wide outside off. David Warner gets down on one knee and smashes it through the cover region. It races away to the fence.
A length ball, around off. Warner blocks it into covers off the front foot.
A short ball, on off. Warner gets behind and blocks it with a straight bat.

Drinks! David Warner is looking like his old self and he will look to convert this into a big score while Steven Smith looks a bit rusty and will want to settle his nerves. South Africa, on the other hand will hope to take a couple of wickets quickly and test the middle order of the Aussies.
A short ball, on off. Smith defends it out watchfully. A probing over by Jansen comes to an end here.
Short ball, down leg, left alone.

JUST SHORT! Marco Jansen serves it touch full, outside off. It shapes away a bit off the deck. Steven Smith gets on his front foot and tries to block it out but he only manage to get a thick outside edge. It does not carry to the man at second slip. Smith gets fortunate this time.
Way too full and wide outside off, moving further away. Smith leaves it alone.
A length ball, on off, defended out.
Marco Jansen starts his spell with a loosener. It is too full, sliding down leg. Warner flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Change from both ends as Marco Jansen (3-0-8-0) is ready to bowl now.
Good length, around leg. Smith gets pinged on his thigh pads as he decides to leave this delivery.
An inswinging delivery, full and on leg. Steven Smith gets inside the line and clips it to the right of mid on. Khaya Zondo is quick to get low to his right and stop the ball.
A single now as this length ball is pushed into covers by the left-hander.

EDGED AND FOUR! David Warner gets his fifth boundary of the innings. It is much fuller, outside off. Warner looks to drive it away. It takes a thick outside edge and goes past the gully fielder. It races away to the fence.
David Warner blocks this length ball off his front foot.
On a length, wide of off. David Warner lets it be.
Back of a length and outside off, Steven Smith offers no shot at it.
FOUR! This is classic Smith! Kagiso Rabada serves this full once more, on off, Steven Smith takes his front foot near the ball and drives it through covers for a beautiful boundary.
Full again but way outside off, Steven Smith chase it but mistimes his drive towards covers.
Kagiso Rabada serves this full and on off, Steven Smith prods forward a bit and lets it go to the keeper.
Back of a length and on middle, Steven Smith blocks it to the right of short leg.
This is on a good length and on off, shaping away, Steven Smith shoulders arms to it.
On a length and on middle, Steven Smith works it towards square leg for a run.
Short of a length and on off, David Warner punches it over point for a single.

FOUR! This is full and outside off, David Warner gets into position early and drives it firmly through covers, but it does not have that much legs in it. Dean Elgar from covers chase and keeps it inside, but the batters run four runs.
Anrich Nortje bangs in a bouncer at 150 clicks, on middle and off, David Warner sways away from it.
Back of a length and around off, David Warner cuts it straight to point again.
This is on a good length and on off, David Warner guides it towards point.
Back of a length and around off, Steven Smith leaves it alone.
This is on a good length and on middle, Steven Smith looks to play at it, but gets squared up and the ball takes an outside edge and goes past the diving gully fielder. Two runs taken!
Back of a length, around off, climbing on the batter. Steven Smith hangs back and blocks it with straight bat.
Fraction short, with some width on offer. Warner dabs it through point and crosses for a single. The MCG is on its feet as Warner gets his half-century in his 100th Test match.
Back of a length, wide outside off. Warner stays back and tries to cut it away. The ball goes back to the bowler off the inner half.
Rabada comes 'round the wicket and angles in a full ball, on off. David Warner tries to drive it away but inside-edges it to mid-wicket.
A dot to end the over! On a good length, on fourth stump. Smith gets behind the line and blocks it to the off side.
Length and outside off. Warner taps it to covers. The fielder dives to his left and makes a good stop. The batters only take a single.
Back of a length, just outside off. David Warner gets across and blocks it back to the bowler.
Steven Smith is the new man at the crease.

OUT! RUN OUT! A huge mix-up in the middle and Marnus Labuschagne sacrifices his wicket. South African players are delighted. Anrich Nortje bowls this on a hard length and on off, David Warner pushes it in front of covers and sets off for the run. The fielder there picks up and has a shy at the batter's end but misses as the ball rolls towards deep square leg. Marnus Labuschagne tries to go for the overthrow but he is well past the batting crease and Warner agrees, but both of them hesitate a bit in the middle. However, Marnus Labuschagne decides to go to the danger end and sacrifices his wicket as David Warner is a long way down the track. Keshav Maharaj throws the ball at the bowler's end where Anrich Nortje collects it and breaks the stumps with an underarm throw. Australia two down now!
Commentary.Howout: run out (Keshav Maharaj / Anrich Nortje)

Commentary.Commentary: Is that a run out? South Africa players think they have got their man here. The umpire takes it upstairs to confirm. The replays suggest that Marnus Labuschagne is short of the crease once the bails are off. South Africa strike against the run of play here.
Anrich Nortje bangs in another sharp bouncer on middle and leg, David Warner this time ducks under it.

David Warner gets hit on the top of his helmet and the physio comes out to get through the concussion protocols. Warner seems to be good now but he is waiting for a new helmet here. It is turning out to be a long delay as Warner is facing some issues with the padding inside his helmet.
FOUR LEG BYES! Anrich Nortje bangs in a good bouncer, on middle, David Warner goes for the pull shot, but misses as the ball deflects off his helmet towards the third man fence for a boundary.
Looks like Rabada has got his rhythm back. He bowls this full and on off, shaping away, Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone again.
Short of a length and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne defends it to the leg side.
Length again and on off, Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone again.
Good shape! Kagiso Rabada serves this a touch fuller and around off, shaping away, Marnus Labuschagne offers no shot at it.
Back of a length and on middle, angling in, David Warner tucks it towards mid-wicket for a single.
This is on a hard length and on the sixth stump line, David Warner lifts his bat up and lets it go to the keeper.
A bit fuller and on off, Marnus Labuschagne moves across and defends it.
This is on a good length and on off, nips back in sharply, Marnus Labuschagne looks to play at it, but misses and gets hit on his thigh pads.
Short of a length and outside off, shaping away, Marnus Labuschagne offers no shot at it.
Back of a length and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne stays there and blocks it out.
Goes fuller and on off, David Warner drives it firmly through covers for a triple. Marnus Labuschagne wants the fourth but he is sent back.
Anrich Nortje also comes around the wicket and bowls this on a hard length, on off, David Warner dabs it toward point.
Back of a length and on leg, angling in, David Warner helps it towards fine leg for one more.
Length again and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne works it towards mid-wicket for one.
This is on a good length and around off, shaping away, Marnus Labuschagne wacthes it through and makes a good leave.
Full and outside off, Marnus Labuschagne lets it go to the keeper.
Kagiso Rabada comes around the wicket and lands this short, on middle, David Warner pulls it towards deep square leg for a run.
On a length and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne knocks it to the right of mid on for a single.
Full again and on middle and leg, Marnus Labuschagne flicks it towards the vacant deep mid-wicket region for three runs.
Full and on off, Marnus Labuschagne defends it to the off side.
This is on a hard length and on off, Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone again.
Short of a length and on off at 150 clicks, Marnus Labuschagne gets on top of it and blocks it back to the bowler.
Touch fuller and outside off, shaping away a bit, Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.
Back of a length and around off, Marnus Labuschagne offers no shot at it.
Fuller one and on the pads, David Warner tucks it through square leg and comes back for the second.
Kagiso Rabada bowls this on a good length and on off, angling away, David Warner lifts his bat up and lets it go to the keeper.
Short of a length and around off, David Warner steers it towards point.
Goes a bit fuller and on middle, shaping in, David Warner pushes it back to the bowler.
This is on a hard length but down the leg, David Warner leaves it alone.
FOUR! Nice shot! Kagiso Rabada lands this short and wide, David Warner accepts the width and cuts it past point for a boundary.
Who will bowl from the other end? It will be Kagiso Rabada.
BEAUTY! Anrich Nortje bowls this on a good length and on the fifth stump line, Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Back of a length and around off, David Warner punches it through covers for three runs.

EDGE AND FOUR! Anrich Nortje serves this full and on off, Marnus Labuschagne looks to drive it on the up, but gets an outside edge as the ball flies between third slip and gully for a boundary.
This is on a good length and outside off again, Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.

The morning session on Day 2 is set to begin. South Africa players take the field. Followed by David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne who walk out with their swords in hand. It will be Anrich Nortje to start with the ball.

In total we saw 11 wickets fall on Day 1. So there is certainly some assistance on offer for the bowlers but we also saw it gets much better for the batters once they get their eye-in. Will the South African seamers be able to threaten the batting line up with a fairly new ball? Or will the Aussies come out all guns blazing and take the game away from the visitors? We shall find out soon.

Hello and a warm welcome to all for Day 2 of this enticing Test match between Australia and South Africa. It is the hosts who are on the driving seat at the moment but the Proteas would look to make early inroads in the morning session. We are surely in for a treat.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right then, that is it from Day 1. Australia trail by 144 runs with 9 wickets in hand. They will want that David Warner continues like this on Day 2 as well and Marnus Labuschagne supports him. South Africa, on the other hand will look to make early inroads in the morning session. It is going to be a good battle. The first ball of Day 2 will be bowled at 5 am IST (11.30 pm GMT, previous day) on 27th December, Tuesday, but as you all know you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

Australia will be pretty satisfied with how things ended on Day 1. Their bowlers initially struggled a bit to get the breakthrough, but it was Scott Boland who provided it. Then it was some individual brilliance from Marnus Labuschagne to run out Dean Elgar which was a huge moment in the innings. In the second session, the wicket became a little bit better for batting and Marco Jansen and Kyle Verreynne took full advantage of it and also were helped by a bit of sloppy fielding as Usman Khawaja dropped Jansen. However, then the man with golden arm, Cameron Green came in and got both these batters in the same over and then absolutely demolished the lower order of South Africa. He registered his maiden five-wicket haul in Test cricket and it will be a bit more special as he did it on Boxing Day. After coming out to bat David Warner made his intentions clear and took on the bowlers and he looked in good touch. Usman Khawaja was the only casualty and it will be Warner and Marnus Labuschagne to continue for them on Day 2 to get them close to the total or even go past it.

After being asked to bat first, the Proteas got off to a very watchful start. Their openers could not stay around for long and Sarel Erwee lost his wicket just before drinks. Then Dean Elgar and Theunis de Bruyn looked good, but the later threw his wicket away which started a mini collapse as they found themselves at 58-4 at Lunch. However, in the post-Lunch session they counter-attacked the Aussies as Kyle Verreynne and Marco Jansen added 112 runs to the board for the sixth wicket with both of them scoring excellent fifties. But as soon as they lost Kyle Verreynne it started another collapse for them as they lost five wickets for just 10 runs and were ultimately bowled out for 189. This gave all the momentum back to the Aussies. They though did manage to get an early wicket Usman Khawaja but there is still a lot to do for them to put the hosts in trouble.

A riveting day of Test cricket comes to an end! We have seen good battle between bat and ball and both teams have fought their way back in this game at certain times. A total of 11 wickets fell for 234 runs were scored and the game is nicely poised at this moment.

Right then, that is it from the second Test and Australia have dominated yet again to seal the series. South Africa, on the other hand have fallen to third place in the World Test Championship standings, and they will need to win the third Test to rectify their position. The third Test will start on 4th of January at 5 am IST (11.30 pm GMT, previous day) at the Sydney Cricket Ground. As you know, our build-up will begin much earlier so do join us for the same. Till then, goodbye and cheers!

Pat Cummins, the victorious skipper says that he is proud of his team and to win against South Africa is a bit more special as they haven't won against them at home for a long time. Adds that Warner and Smith batted really well in the heat and also credits Starc and Green to perform regardless of their injuries. Mentions that Warner was up for this game and to score 200 in his 100th Test is awesome. Tells that Carey did really well to get his maiden Test hundred in a Boxing Day Test. Ends by saying the Lyon just wounded himself but will be available for the next game and says that this win is a bit more special because of Shane Warne.

Dean Elgar, the captain of South Africa in for a chat. He says that this loss is not easy at the moment. Adds that they haven't been upto speed with their game. Mentions that it is the inexperience in the batting line-up that has started to hurt them a lot now. Although, says that this is a great chance for the youngsters to steal their spot here. Informs they need to move on very quickly as they final test is around the corner.

David Warner wins the Man of the Match award for his sensational knock of 200 runs. He says that it is a phenomenal achievement to win this Boxing Day Test and seal the series. Adds that they just wanted provide entertainment to the fans that came out in numbers and credits Cameron Green, Mitchell Starc and Alex Carey for their performances. Mentions that this knock will be a special one for him and tells that he is feeling fit and the aim is play in the World Cup next year.
Stay tuned for the presentation...

Mitchell Starc is in for a quick chat. He says that this is a big win for them. Adds that it was nice to contribute to the team but tells that he will be out of action for a few weeks. Mentions that he wants to come back for the Indian tour but will have to assess the injury more. Credits David Warner for his double century and jokingly says that he is the first man to score a 200 and get out on the first ball. Also, credits Alex Carey for his hundred and ends by saying that it was a great win.

Australia lost an early wicket in the form Usman Khawaja but that did not stop them from harming the opposition in any way or form as David Warner stabled the ship alongwith Marnus Labuschagne with a stand of 54 runs. The latter gave away his wicket through a run-out to keep Warner at the crease on his 100th Test match. Warner made sure he makes this innings count and boy, he did it by racking up a double-century after going through a lean patch in the Test format recently. Steven Smith supported him well but fell out on 85 runs. Later, Alex Carey smacked his maiden ton to add on to the misery of the Proteas. Travis Head and Cameron Green also played a valuable knock and chipped in with half-centuries. The latter though played through a lot of pain as he injured his finger and sat out during South Africa's second innings with the blade. Eventually, Australia ended up posting 575 on the board which turned out to be too much for the Proteas.

It all began when Pat Cummins won the toss and opted to bowl first once again in this series. Everyone was hoping for the wicket to be a batting friendly one but with the rain predicted over the course of this Test match Cummins agreed on a questionable decision. Although, his bowlers backed him really well and bundled out South Africa for 189 runs. Once again Australia were able to keep the Proteas under the 200-run mark which raises a lot of questions about the visitors batting strength at the moment. Except Kyle Verreynne and Marco Jansen no one else could turn up with the blade for them. For the Aussies though it was Cameron Green who turned on the heat with the ball in the first innings with his five-wicket haul.

This has been a solid bowling performance by Australia. They never let the South Africa breathe easily at the crease. The pair of Mitchell Starc and Pat Cummins caused a lot of problems with the new ball in hand, while the former showed some great determination to bowl well with an injured finger. These two bowlers returned with a wicket each. Scott Boland chipped in with a couple. Although, it was the GOAT, Nathan Lyon who came to the party in the post-Lunch session on Day 4 to take a three-fer while Steven Smith took the final wicket to put this game to bed. Pat Cummins would be very happy with the way his boys have backed his decision throughout this Test match.

South Africa came to bat in the final session on Day 3 with the deficit being 386 runs. This was always going to be an uphill task for the Proteas looking at current form with the blade in hand. They could only face 7 overs on the moving day as the rain forced the umpires to call for stumps early. Although, it might've been a relief for them as they were already a man down. In the morning session on Day 4, Sarel Erwee and Theunis de Bruyn started well and were being solid in their defense from the get go. They built a stubborn stand of 47 runs off 94 deliveries but they lost both the batters in quick succession. Soon, Khaya Zondo had to head to back to the dressing room due to a run out. Temba Bavuma kept one end intact but saw quite a few wickets fall at the other end, as he smacked a half-ton. Although, he was a part of two run outs in the middle which eventually put him under a lot of pressure and he slipped out. Later on, none of the tail-enders could whack their tails for long and the Proteas bundled out for 204 runs.

Australia seal the series 2-0 with a convincing win over the Proteas at the Melbourne Cricket Ground by an innings and 182 runs. It has been one-way traffic throughout this Test match and Australia have certainly outclassed their opponents here.

OUT! TIMBER! Steven Smith gets the last wicket! That is that then from this Test! It is a fitting end as a leg-spinner finishes the game for Australia. Smith loops this up above the eye-line of the batter, on leg, Lungi Ngidi goes for the big heave, but plays all around it as the ball turns in from outside leg to rattle the off pole. A ball Shane Warne would have been proud of. Australian players are delighted and the handshakes are going on in the middle. Australia win by an innings and 182 runs to seal the series!
Commentary.Howout: b Steven Smith

Nathan Lyon pushes this quicker through the air, on off, straightens after hitting the deck, Marco Jansen looks to block it out, but plays down the wrong line and misses to get rapped around his back leg. The post-Lunch session is set to begin. The Australian players are seen to be in a huddle before they stride out to the middle. Followed by Temba Bavuma and Kyle Verreynne who walk out to bat for South Africa. Scott Boland to start with the ball this time.
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

The Proteas looked solid at the beginning of the Day as both Sarel Erwee and Theunis de Bruyn were pretty good with their defenses. However, they lost both of them in quick succession, and then a disastrous run out of Khaya Zondo put them on the back foot. After that, Temba Bavuma and Kyle Verreynne steadied the ship for them and added over 50 runs to the board. Both of them looked to play shots and take on the bowlers whenever the opportunity arrived. They will look to continue the same in the next session as well. Australia, on the other hand, are still in the driving seat, and this break would probably help them more. Mitchell Starc and Scott Boland provided them the breakthroughs, and Travis Head showed some smart fielding to score a run-out. They will be happy with the three wickets, but they know they have to break this partnership to get into the middle order of South Africa. So, they will come out with more fire, and it will be an exciting battle to watch. Do join us at 7.40 am IST (2.10 am GMT) for the post-Lunch session.

Lunch! South Africa still trail by 266 runs and are behind in the game. However, they did make a good recovery after losing their way a bit early in the session. Their focus will be to put pressure on the bowlers without losing wickets, while the Aussies will hope to use this break to their advantage and get through the South African batting order as quickly as possible.

South Africa are in a spot of bother here.

We are ready for action on Day 4 in this Boxing Day Test!  Australian players make their way out in the middle and take their respective field positions. They are followed by the two batters, Theunis de Bruyn and Sarel Erwee for South Africa. Pat Cummins to start proceedings with the ball. Here we go...

South Africa did not have a good start to their second innings as they lost their skipper, Dean Elgar, quite early. However, they did not bat that long as rain played spoilsport after Tea on Day 3. They will have to come out to bat with a fresh mindset and try to take advantage of the conditions. Their key players will be Sarel Erwee, Temba Bavuma, and Kyle Verreynne, who will have to score the bulk of runs. Australia, on the other hand, knows that they just need to hit the right line and length and they can get through this South African batting order. Their main concern will be that Mitchell Starc is not fully fit and will be bowling through pain. So, Pat Cummins and Scott Boland will have to take on more responsibility. It is Day 4, and there may be some rough patches, which could help Nathan Lyon get some grip, and he may be the most effective in bowling out the Proteas. Also, South Africa have not been able to cross the 200-run mark in their last seven Test innings which could give more encouragement to the Aussies to get the job done. It is going to be an exciting Day of Test cricket.

Hello and a warm welcome, folks! We are almost ready for Day 4 of the second Test between Australia and South Africa. This could prove to be the decisive Day as the hosts are nine wickets away from victory while the Proteas are trailing by 371 runs. This Test has provided us with a lot of drama, and we can expect nothing short of that here too.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, the inevitable has happened. The rain gods continue to make their presence feel at the Melbourne Cricket Ground and the umpires have finally decided to call it stumps on Day 3 after a long delay. South Africa only got to bat for 7 overs in the post-Tea session. They have already lost their skipper and the rest of the batting order certainy have their task cut out. For Australia, Mitchell Starc splattered blood on his whites and bowled 4 overs with unbearable pain. That is some great effort by the left-arm seamer. Although, it was the skipper, Pat Cummins who lead the bowling attack from the front. He took the only wicket so far in the innings. He could've got two wickets but David Warner dropped one in at first slip. Australia currently are on the driving seat here and would be hoping to put things to bed on Day 4. Will South Africa be able to put up a solid fightback? Or will the Aussies march on their merry way? To find out, do join us at 4.30 am IST (11 pm GMT, previous day). Until then, take care and goodbye.
Update 11.21 am IST (5.51 am GMT) - It is still raining but it is not heavy. The covers are on for now but this should not be a long wait.

Update 10.53 am IST (5.23 am GMT) - Oh dear! It has started to drizzle and the umpires have asked the players to head out of the field. The groundstaff now rushes to the middle of the park and put the covers on. Hopefully, it is just a passing shower and the delay is not a long one.
